ion of Twelfth-Century Jewish-Christian Relations -- t13. ‘De Judaea, muta et surda’: Jewish Conversion in Gerald of Wales’s Life of Saint Remigius -- t14. Dehumanizing the Jew at the Funeral of the Virgin Mary in the Thirteenth Century (c. 1170–c. 1350) -- t15. Massacre and Memory: Ethics and Method in Recent Scholarship on Jewish Martyrdom -- t16. The Future of the Jews of York -- tAfterword: Violence, Memory and the Traumatic Middle Ages -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe shocking massacre of the Jews in York, 1190, is here re-examined in its historical context along with the circumstances and processes through which Christian and Jewish neighbours became enemies and victims.The mass suicide and murder of the men, women and children of the Jewish community in York on 16 March 1190 is one of the most scarring events in the history of Anglo-Judaism, and an aspect of England's medieval past which is widely remembered around the world. However, the York massacre was in fact only one of a series of attacks on communities of Jews across England in 1189-90; they were violent expressions of wider new constructs of the nature of Christian and Jewish communities, and the targeted outcries of local townspeople, whose emerging urban politics were enmeshed within the swiftly developing structures of royal government. This new collection considers the massacreas central to the narrative of English and Jewish history around 1200. Its chapters broaden the contexts within which the narrative is usually considered and explore how a narrative of events in 1190 was built up, both at the timeand in following years. They also focus on two main strands: the role of narrative in shaping events and their subsequent perception; and the degree of convivencia between Jews and Christians and consideration of the circumstances and processes through which neighbours became enemies and victims. Sarah Rees Jones is Senior Lecturer in History, Sethina Watson Lecturer, at the University of York. Contributors: Sethina Watson, Sarah Rees Jones, Joe Hillaby, Nicholas Vincent, Alan Cooper, Robert C. Stacey, Paul Hyams, Robin R. Mundill, Thomas Roche, Eva de Visscher, Pinchas Roth, Ethan Zadoff, Anna Sapir Abulafia, Heather Blurton, Matthew Mesley, Carlee A.Bradbury, Hannah Johnson, Jeffrey J. Cohen, Anthony Bale  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJewszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500vCongresses. 0aMassacreszEnglandzYorkxHistoryyTo 1500vCongresses. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Judaism.  aChristian and Jewish communities.  aChristian.  aEngland.  aJewish studies.  aJews.  aYork Massacre.  aYork.  aconvivencia.  amassacre.  amedieval history.  aroyal government.  atwelfth century.  aurban politics.1 aAbulafia, Anna Sapir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBale, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlurton, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradbury, Carlee A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradbury, Carlee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Jeffrey Jerome, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Visscher, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHillaby, Joe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyams, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJ